  "text": "In addition to SM HSTs, some necrotrophic plant pathogens secrete small toxic peptides that induce host necrosis or chlorosis, and can act as key determinants of fungal virulence or pathogenicity [CITATION_1] . These ribosome-synthesized HSTs act as effectors of necrotrophy (Friesen et al., 2008a, b) . Much of what is known today on the mode of action of proteinaceous HSTs and their interaction with host susceptibility genes comes from detailed studies on two important Dothideomycete necrotrophic wheat pathogens, Ptr [CITATION_2] and S. nodorum (Table 2; [CITATION_3] .",
